message.
The
gipsies
did
not
wait
for
the
operations
of
justice;
they
took
themselves
off
in
a
hurry.
The
young
ladies
of
Highbury
might
have
walked
again
in
safety
before
their
panic
began,
and
the
whole
history
dwindled
soon
into
a
matter
of
little
importance
but
to
Emma
and
her
nephews:
in
her
imagination
it
maintained
its
ground,
and
Henry
and
John
were
still
asking
every
day
for
the
story
of
Harriet
and
the
gipsies,
and
still
tenaciously
setting
her
right
if
she
varied
in
the
slightest
