and
after
sitting
down
and
hesitating,
thus
began:
"Miss
Woodhouse
if
you
are
at
leisure
I
have
something
that
I
should
like
to
tell
you
a
sort
of
confession
to
make
and
then,
you
know,
it
will
be
over."
Emma
was
a
good
deal
surprized;
but
begged
her
to
speak.
There
was
a
seriousness
in
Harriet's
manner
which
prepared
her,
quite
as
much
as
her
words,
for
something
more
than
ordinary.
"It
is
my
duty,
and
I
am
sure
it
is
my
wish,"
she
continued,
"to
have
no
